<br>
I have a little tip for comic coloring: Highlights are placed where the light hits the peak of an object while shadow is placed on spots hidden away from the lightsource and edges of an object. It's not realistic but it might hold you over untill you get the book to study. <p>Be well, do good work, and keep in touch. -Writer's Almanac NPR</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/upuhfyn.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Puhfyn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/28/02 8:19:19 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4062.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Light and Shadow</span><hr size=1> just keep in mind the 3D-ness, or form, of the object.  then also keep in mind where the light is coming from.  the area on the backside of objects that the light doesnt hit is much darker than the area hit directly by light. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/ujspuonti.showPublicProfile?language=EN>JSPuonti</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>In Brilliant Color</span><br> <font color=#336699>(7/29/02 1:50:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4062.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.saunalahti.fi/jspuonti/polyav.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Light and Shadow</span><hr size=1> Something I've noticed in my own pictures is that I'm often &quot;affraid&quot; of dark shadows. Even if the image displays something where pure black shadows would be possible (like a room with only one light source), I still tend to leave some color in absolutely dark areas.<br>
<br>
A great way to get yourself used to dark shadows is to work on a black background instead of white - I assume you do most if not all of your CG'ing over a white background. White background is bad because your eyes get used to the &quot;lightness level&quot; of it, and you tend to color the picture accordingly (with relatively light shades of colors). If you color a picture with a white background and then change the background to white, you'll probably notice what I mean - the image seems washed out (even though against a white background it seemed nice).<br>
<br>
For this excercise, find a lineart of your own or done by someone else, create a new image with a black background, paste the lineart onto a new layer and invert it. Now set the lineart layer to &quot;lighten&quot; and layer opacity to something like 10% (so that you can see the lineart as a faint &quot;ghost&quot;, not pure white lines). Then create a new layer between the black background and the lineart layer, and select the brush tool.<br>
<br>
Now it's time to think about the image for a bit. You probably have a lineart of a person, if this board is any indication of the most common subject of a picture. Decide where you will have the source of light - you can start with easy placement such as &quot;directly on the right side of the person&quot; or &quot;directly above him&quot; and later on go with &quot;above and before the person&quot; and so on.<br>
<br>
Select white (or off-white) color, 5-10 per cent opacity for the brush tool and start applying the color gradually in those areas where you think the light would reach. For example if the light source is straight above the character (who's standing straight and looking forward), you'll have light on parts of his forehead (depending on his hair), on top of his hair, on top of his ears (depending on hair), on top of the bridge of his nose and nostrils, and possibly on his top lip (where the nose is not casting a shadow), on the upper side of his cheeks and so on.<br>
<br>
Apply absolutely no color in those areas you think would be shadowed. In the above example these would be his eyes and the indention surrounding them, under his nose, under his jaw, under his lips and on his forehead in those parts where hair casts a shadow.<br>
<br>
You can make the highlights as smooth or harsh (animation-style) as you want - the main point is that you realize where the shadows and highlights are. You don't have to worry about colors, just worry about the lighting <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p><hr><b>Want to color my lineart?</b> Otherwise alter something I've created? Read my <a href="http://pub25.ezboard.com/ujspuonti.showPublicProfile?language=EN"><b>profile</b></a> for further information before proceeding!</p><i></i></td></tr></table><br><font color=#336699>- </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs>Polykarbon BBS</a><font color=#336699> - </font><a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2>Photoshop and Art questions</a> <font color=#336699> - </font><a href="http://www.polykarbon.com">Polykarbon: Manga & Photoshop</a><font color=#336699> - </font><br><br><table border=0 align=center><tr><td align=center></td><td><img src="http://www.ezboard.com/image/spacer.gif" width=15 height=1 border=0></td><td align=center></td></tr></table><CENTER><!-- START BOTTOM ARTS AD SCRIPT -->
